{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512489"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:56:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:56:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.02,0.09,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116476"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4503"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98475"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"82"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116476"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with chest palpitations and light-headedness for the past hour. He states that he was walking to work when he experienced a sudden onset of symptoms. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a non-smoker. He drinks four to five standard drinks most days. One examination, his pulse rate is 180/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, and SpO2 99% on room air. An ECG is performed and shows a regular rhythm tachycardia with a narrow QRS (approximately 90 milliseconds).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Modified valsalva manoeuvre","Digoxin","Adenosine","Metoprolol","Amlodipine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENarrow-complex tachycardias\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eare defined as rhythms with a QRS complex duration less than 100 milliseconds and a ventricular rate greater than 100 beats/minute. Although virtually all narrow-complex tachydysrhythmias originate from a focus above the ventricles, the term supraventricular tachycardia (SVT)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis conventionally used to denote those rhythms aside from sinus tachycardia, atrial tachycardia, AF, and atrial flutter [eg, atrioventricular nodal reentry tachycardia (AVNRT) and atrioventricular reentry tachycardia (AVRT)].\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManoeuvres that increase vagal tone\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ehave been shown to slow conduction through the AV node and convert SVT back to sinus rhythm. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emodified valsalva manoeuvre\u003C/strong\u003E is one particular move which has been shown to increase vagal tone. The manoeuvre involves placing the patient in a semi-recumbent position and getting them to forcefully exhale into a 10ml syringe to generate a high pressure. This is followed by laying the patient supine and passively raising their legs to 45 degrees for 15 seconds. The patient is then returned to the semi-recumbent position for a further 45 seconds before re-assessment of cardiac rhythm. Additional moves include the carotid sinus massage and facial immersion in cold water. If these interventions are unsuccessful or contraindicated then pharmacological measures should be implemented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenosine\u003C/strong\u003E is a short acting atrioventricular (AV) nodal blocking agent which significantly slows conduction time. This effect occurs by activation of specific potassium channels, driving potassium extracellularly and inhibiting calcium influx, thus disrupting the resting potential of the slow nodal cardiac myocyte. Because it is so fast acting, it must be delivered through a large vein (eg, the antecubital fossa) with a rapid IV fluid bolus. It is important to monitor the patient and ensure ready access to resuscitation equipment and senior mangement as there is a chance of serious ventricular response acceleration following initial AV blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin \u003C/strong\u003Eis an antidysrhythmic and ionotropic but it has a slow onset that may take several hours or more to work as its maximal effect is at 2-6 hours. It also slows conduction through the AV node by increasing cardiac vagal tone modulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol \u003C/strong\u003Ein 2.5-5 mg IV boluses are also an appropriate method of pharmacologically restoring sinus rhythm in SVT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine \u003C/strong\u003Eis a dihydropyridine type calcium channel blocker and is thus inappropriate for converting SVT to sinus rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the above pharmacological interventions fail to convert to sinus rhythm then direct current (DC) cardioversion, IV amiodarone or overdrive pacing may be required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Unless contraindicated, manouevres which increase vagal stimulation should be attempted prior to pharmacological management for supra ventricular tachycardia (SVT).","Modified valsalva manoeuvre is a method of increasing vagal tone which may convert SVT to sinus rhythm."],"references":["Abdulhamid, A.S., Almehmadi, F., Ghaddaf, A.A. et al. Modified valsalva versus standard valsalva for cardioversion of supraventricular tachycardia: systematic review and meta-analysis. Int J Arrhythm. 2021;22:2.Available at: https://arrhythmia.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s42444-021-00030-2","Paroxysmal supra ventricular tachycardia. In: ETG complete [online]. https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98475"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98475"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4503"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116476"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Managemen